{"type":"assistant","uuid":"539a7ac2-5d76-4b7e-b022-3ece53537d16","session_id":"1d994fb9-a16e-4807-a010-cfcd3a8ecb20","message":{"id":"539a7ac2-5d76-4b7e-b022-3ece53537d16","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The patient is a 20-year-old male with:\n- Chief complaint: worsening asthma/wheezing for 3 days\n- Diagnosis: Mild to moderate acute asthma exacerbation (J45.901)\n- Past medical history: Bronchial asthma since 2018, not on regular controller therapy\n- Current medications: None (ran out of Symbicort 5 years ago)\n- Allergies: None listed\n- Physical exam: Bilateral wheezing, no cyanosis, no respiratory distress\n- Vitals: BP 122/78, HR 92, RR 22, SpO2 96%, T 36.8°C\n- Labs: Normal\n- Renal/hepatic function: Normal\n- Not pregnant\n\nThis is a classic acute asthma exacerbation in a young adult who's not on regular controller therapy. The patient ran out of his Symbicort (salmeterol/fluticasone) 5 years ago and hasn't been using it regularly.\n\nClinical decision:\n1. This is an acute exacerbation triggered by pollen exposure\n2. Patient needs:\n   - Quick relief: Short-acting beta agonist (SABA) like salbutamol/albuterol for immediate relief\n   - Possibly oral corticosteroids if moderate exacerbation\n   - Re-initiation of controller therapy: Inhaled corticosteroid (ICS) or ICS/LABA combination\n\nLet me think about the severity:\n- Mild-moderate exacerbation\n- SpO2 96% (good)\n- No respiratory distress\n- RR 22 (slightly elevated)\n- HR 92 (slightly elevated)\n- Wheezing present\n\nThis sounds like a mild to moderate exacerbation. The patient should receive:\n1. SABA (salbutamol) inhaler for rescue\n2. Oral prednisone if needed (but might not be necessary for mild exacerbation)\n3. Controller therapy: ICS or ICS/LABA\n\nActually, looking at the diagnosis again: \"支气管哮喘急性发作（轻中度）\" - mild to moderate acute exacerbation.\n\nFor mild-moderate exacerbation:\n- SABA PRN via metered-dose inhaler\n- Oral corticosteroids may be considered if poor response to SABA\n- Step up controller therapy\n\nGiven that the patient has been using salmeterol/fluticasone in the past and it worked, and he's not on any regular therapy now, I should:\n1. Prescribe SABA (salbutamol) inhaler for rescue\n2. Prescribe ICS/LABA combination (like salmeterol/fluticasone or budesonide/formoterol) for controller therapy\n3. Possibly a short course of oral prednisone if exacerbation is moderate\n\nLet me check what medications are available in the formulary by querying the drug API.\n\nActually, I should prescribe based on standard asthma management guidelines:\n1. Salbutamol inhaler (SABA) - rescue medication\n2. Budesonide/formoterol or salmeterol/fluticasone (ICS/LABA) - controller\n3. Possibly prednisone oral for the exacerbation\n\nFor a mild-moderate exacerbation, oral corticosteroids are often prescribed for 5-7 days. The GINA guidelines suggest a short course of OCS for exacerbations.\n\nLet me prescribe:\n1. Salbutamol inhaler 100μg/puff - 2 puffs PRN, up to 4 times daily\n2. Budesonide/formoterol 160/4.5μg - 2 puffs bid (maintenance and reliever therapy approach)\n3. Prednisone 5mg tablets - 30-40mg daily for 5-7 days (for the exacerbation)\n\nActually, I need to be careful about the dosing. Let me think about this more carefully:\n\nFor acute exacerbation management:\n- SABA: Salbutamol 100-200μg (1-2 puffs) PRN, can repeat every 4-6 hours\n- Oral prednisone: 30-50mg daily for 5-7 days for mild-moderate exacerbation\n- Controller: ICS or ICS/LABA\n\nThe patient was previously on salmeterol/fluticasone, so restarting ICS/LABA makes sense.\n\nLet me now query the drug information to get the exact specifications and then create the prescription","signature":""}],"model":"hy3-preview-ioa","role":"assistant","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"type":"message","usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":null,"cache_read_input_tokens":null,"cache_creation":null,"server_tool_use":null,"service_tier":null}},"pare